  "text": "# Memory Pressure Pod Eviction in Kubernetes\n\n## Memory Pressure Eviction Thresholds\n\nThe memory pressure eviction thresholds are defined in the `pkg/kubelet/eviction/` package in kubernetes/kubernetes:\n\n### Threshold Signals (pkg/kubelet/eviction/api/types.go)\nTwo primary signals trigger memory-based evictions:\n- `SignalMemoryAvailable` (constant: \"memory.available\") - Triggers eviction when available memory drops below threshold\n- `SignalAllocatableMemoryAvailable` (constant: \"allocatableMemory.available\") - Triggers eviction based on allocatable memory available to pods\n\n### Default Thresholds\nThe default memory pressure eviction thresholds vary by platform:\n- **Linux** (pkg/kubelet/eviction/defaults_linux.go): `memory.available: 100Mi` - Kubelet will evict pods when less than 100MB of memory is available\n- **Windows** (pkg/kubelet/eviction/defaults_windows.go): `memory.available: 500Mi` - Kubelet will evict pods when less than 500MB of memory is available\n\nThese defaults are stored in the `DefaultEvictionHard` map variable, which is used by the kubelet if no explicit eviction thresholds are configured.\n\n## Eviction Manager Decision Logic\n\n### Core Configuration (pkg/kubelet/eviction/types.go)\nThe `Config` struct defines eviction parameters:\n- `Thresholds []evictionapi.Threshold` - The set of conditions monitored to trigger eviction\n- `PressureTransitionPeriod` - Duration to wait before transitioning out of a pressure condition\n- `MaxPodGracePeriodSeconds` - Maximum allowed grace period when terminating pods\n\n### Main Control Loop (pkg/kubelet/eviction/eviction_manager.go)\nThe `managerImpl` type implements the `Manager` interface with the critical `synchronize()` method that:\n1. Gets current resource usage observations from the node\n2. Compares observations against configured thresholds\n3. Determines which thresholds are met using `thresholdsMet()` helper\n4. Applies grace periods and tracks node conditions\n5. Ranks pods for eviction using signal-specific ranking functions\n6. Evicts the highest-priority pod by calling `evictPod()`\n\n### Threshold Evaluation (pkg/kubelet/eviction/helpers.go)\nThe `thresholdsMet()` function evaluates each threshold:\n- Retrieves observed available resource for the signal\n- Compares against the threshold value: if `available < threshold`, threshold is met\n- Returns list of met thresholds for the eviction manager to process\n\n### Pod Ranking for Memory Pressure (pkg/kubelet/eviction/helpers.go)\nWhen memory pressure is detected, the `rankMemoryPressure()` function ranks pods for eviction by:\n1. **Usage vs. Requests**: Pods exceeding memory requests come first\n2. **Priority**: Higher priority pods are ranked lower (evicted last)\n3. **Memory Usage Above Requests**: Pods with higher memory consumption above requests are evicted first\n\n### Eviction Signal Mapping (pkg/kubelet/eviction/helpers.go)\nThe `buildSignalToRankFunc()` function maps memory signals to their ranking function:\n- Both `SignalMemoryAvailable` and `SignalAllocatableMemoryAvailable` use `rankMemoryPressure()`\n- This ensures consistent pod ranking behavior for both memory-based eviction signals\n\n## Complete Eviction Flow\n\nWhen a node experiences memory pressure:\n1. The kubelet's eviction manager's `synchronize()` loop (running every ~10 seconds) collects memory statistics\n2. Compares available memory against thresholds from config (default: 100Mi on Linux)\n3. If memory.available < threshold, the `thresholdsMet()` function identifies this threshold as met\n4. The `rankMemoryPressure()` function ranks active pods for eviction\n5. The pod with highest eviction priority is selected and terminated via `evictPod()`\n6. The pod's status is set to `PodFailed` with reason `\"Evicted\"` and a message indicating memory pressure\n7. This process repeats until memory available rises above the threshold\n\n## Related Configuration\n\nThese mechanisms can be configured via kubelet flags:\n- `--eviction-hard`: Hard eviction thresholds (e.g., `memory.available=100Mi`)\n- `--eviction-soft`: Soft eviction thresholds with grace periods\n- `--eviction-pressure-transition-period`: Duration before transitioning out of pressure condition\n- `--eviction-max-pod-grace-period`: Maximum grace period for soft evictions\n\nThe eviction system works in conjunction with QoS class (Guaranteed, Burstable, BestEffort) to prioritize which pods get evicted under memory pressure."
}

